<p><strong>Coast Horned Lizard (<em>Phrynosoma blainvillii</em>)</strong></p>
<p><strong>Family: </strong>Iguanidae<br />
<strong>Genus Species: </strong><em>Phrynosoma blainvillii</em><br />
<strong>Common Name: </strong>Coast Horned Lizard<br /><p>
<p><strong>Identification</strong></p>
<p> The Coast Horned Lizard has a body length of 2½-4½ inches. It has two horns at the back of the head, which are longer than the rest of its horns, with bases that are separated. It has two rows of pointed fringe scales on each side of the body. It also has 2-3 rows of enlarged pointed scales on each side of the throat. General coloration ranges from yellowish, brown, reddish, or gray. It has wavy dark blotches on the back and a pair of large dark blotches on the neck. It is cream, beige, or yellow below, usually with spots of dusky. For a more detailed overview of this species see 〔<a href="http://www.californiaherps.com/lizards/pages/p.blainvillii.html">California Herps</a>〕.</p>
<p><strong> </strong></p>
<p><strong>Habitat Associations and Natural History</strong></p>
<p>This lizard inhabits scrubland, grassland, coniferous forests, and broadleaf woodlands. It prefers areas that are open for basking, patches of loose soil where it can buy, and have plenty of ants and other insect prey, such as termites, beetles, wasps, flies and grasshoppers. Females lay clutches of 6-49 eggs between April-July.</p>
